<font color="#FF0000">HISTORY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 27  6:44:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All Concerned:<br><br>
Joe has cast sufficient doubt on suicide figures such as the ones I got from Marilyn Young's history, THe Vietnam Wars, to make me use the lower figures when I lecture on this.  My question is primarily directed at him, but maybe the rest of you can help.  Here's my problem:  since I'm not a historian, I've relied on the histories that I know about for much of the historical &quot;facts&quot; I use when I teach about 'Nam.  I use Stanley Karnow's &quot;Vietnam:  A History&quot;, Young's &quot;The Vietnam Wars...&quot;, Fitzgerald's &quot;Fire in the Lake...&quot;, and Gelb's &quot;The Irony of Vietnam...&quot;.   In Young's case, she makes no bones about her perspective, which is, for lack of a better way to describe it, &quot;anti-US&quot;.  I appreciate the fact that she doesn't hide her particular bias.  Another history that I just got, but can't force myself to read because the author is TOO &quot;anti-US&quot; is Kolko's &quot;Anatomy of a War&quot;.  My question is, are there other histories that I should be using to &quot;get my facts straight&quot;?  Oh yeah, forgot Tuchman's &quot;The March of Folly&quot;.  That was a fun read, but I don't use it.  Anyway, give me your suggestions, please.
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


